In PHP, a common yet subtle error arises when dealing with string comparisons using the loose comparison operator (`==`) instead of the strict comparison operator (`===`). This can lead to unexpected behavior due to PHP's type juggling. For instance, comparing a string '0' with an integer 0 using `==` will return true, whereas using `===` will return false because the data types differ.  Another example is comparing a string with a boolean value.  The loose comparison may result in an unexpected true when the intent is to check if they are the same type and value.